04649nam a22007215i 9781487573966DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191996onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875739667 a10.3138/97814875739662doi  a(DE-B1597)536901  a(OCoLC)1102655781  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHQ1064.C38bS64 1996eb 7aBUS0500402bisacsh04a305.26/09712201 aSnell, James G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Citizen's Wage :bThe State and the Elderly in Canada, 1900–1951 /cJames G. Snell. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Daily Lives -- t2. Institutionalizing the Dependent Elderly: The First Old Age Homes -- t3. The Family and Intergenerational Support -- t4. Property and the Culture of Entitlement -- t5. Agency among Old Age Pensioners -- t6. Organizing Politically: The First Grey Lobby -- t7. Shifting Policies of Old Age Pensions -- t8. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tA Note on Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough we inevitably grow old, the social, cultural, and economic characteristics associated with aging are neither natural nor inevitable. James Snell brings a historian’s perspective to the problems of aging and the discourse that surrounds it, a discourse that affects both public policy and the way we think about older people. At the beginning of the twentieth century, the elderly were coming to be thought of as a distinct group in society, whose members were inherently weak, sick, and dependent. Poorhouses were slowly being converted to old age homes, and new laws tried to force families to support their elderly parents. The state would supply only limited assistance to those who needed it. The Old Age Pension program, initiated in Canada in 1927, began to change society’s approach to the elderly. Over time individual pensioners learned to manipulate the program to their best advantage and, as a group, they began to assert their common interests, forming the first ‘grey lobby’ to pressure state bureaucrats and politicians to improve both policy and practice. The economic troubles of the 1930s and the early war years reinforced new views of the state as well as a culture of entitlement among the elderly and their families, and many other groups. By mid-century the redefinition of old age was reflected in state policies that offered the elderly new status as ‘senior citizens’ and provided them with new forms of support – particularly universal pensions and health care – captured in the phrase ‘a citizen’s wage.’  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aOlder peoplexGovernment policyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aOlder peoplexServices forzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Personal Finance / Retirement Planning.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757396640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487573966423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487573966.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK